🟡 **MEDIUM** `dmatrix/src/lib.rs:58` – Inefficient design matrix construction
The `Builder` creates a `Vec<Vec<f64>>` to store columns, which are then copied element-by-element into a final `ndarray::Array2`. This approach involves multiple allocations and can be inefficient.

→ **Fix:** Refactor the `Builder` to allocate a single flat `Vec<f64>` and append column data directly. This vector can then be wrapped into an `Array2` with minimal overhead.

```rust
// In dmatrix/src/lib.rs

// Refactor the Builder struct
pub struct Builder {
    n_rows: usize,
    data: Vec<f64>,
    n_cols: usize,
}

impl Builder {
    pub fn new(n_rows: usize) -> Self {
        Self {
            n_rows,
            data: Vec::new(),
            n_cols: 0,
        }
    }

    pub fn add_intercept(&mut self) {
        self.data.extend(vec![1.0; self.n_rows]);
        self.n_cols += 1;
    }

    pub fn add_continuous(&mut self, values: &[f64]) -> Result<(), MatrixError> {
        if values.len() != self.n_rows {
            // ... error handling
        }
        self.data.extend_from_slice(values);
        self.n_cols += 1;
        Ok(())
    }

    pub fn build(self) -> Array2<f64> {
        if self.data.is_empty() {
            return Array2::zeros((self.n_rows, 0));
        }
        // This is efficient as it just wraps the existing Vec
        Array2::from_shape_vec((self.n_rows, self.n_cols), self.data)
            .expect("Shape and data length should be consistent")
    }
}
```
*Note: This requires changing `add_continuous` to accept a slice `&[f64]` and updating call sites to pass references instead of owned vectors, which also helps address the next issue.*

